🧵 1️⃣ What Is a Virtual Thread?

First understand the old model

🟠 Before (Java 8, 11, 17)

If you create:

new Thread(() -> doWork()).start();

That thread is:

👉 Mapped 1-to-1 with an OS thread

Meaning:

1 Java thread = 1 Operating System thread

Problems:

-OS threads are heavy
-Limited (few thousands max)
-Large stack memory (1MB per thread default)
-Context switching is expensive

So if you create 100,000 threads → 💥 system crash or huge memory usage.

🔵 Now: Virtual Threads (Java 21+, available in Java 25)

Virtual Threads come from Project Loom.

Now:

Many Java threads  →  Few OS threads

Instead of:

1 Java thread = 1 OS thread

We have:

100,000 virtual threads
       ↓
Scheduled on maybe 8–16 real OS threads


🧠 What does that mean?

Virtual threads are:

a.Very lightweight
b.Created in huge numbers
c.Managed by the JVM, not the OS
d.Parked and resumed efficiently


📦 How are they different internally?

Platform Thread (old):

(i)    Has its own OS stack
(ii)   Heavy
(iii)  OS does scheduling
(iv)   Virtual Thread
(v)    Stack stored in heap
(vi)   JVM scheduler manages it
(vii)  When blocked (like I/O), it is unmounted
(viii) OS thread is freed for other work


🧠 Simple Analogy

Old model:

Each customer gets a dedicated waiter.

Virtual thread model:

Few waiters serve many customers efficiently.

🎯 Why This Matters for GC

Since virtual thread stacks are stored in heap:

-They are visible to GC
-More scalable
-Better memory usage
-Less pressure compared to thousands of OS stacks



🧵 PART 1: Virtual Threads (Explained Like You’ve Never Seen Threads Before)

Step 1: What is a Thread?

A thread is simply:
-A path of execution inside your program.

When your program runs:

a.Main thread starts
b.It executes instructions line by line

If you create another thread:

new Thread(() -> doWork()).start();

You now have:

-Main thread
-One extra thread

Both run independently.

🟠 Old Model (Platform Threads)

Before Java 21:

1 Java Thread = 1 OS Thread

What is OS Thread?

It is created and managed by:

Windows / Linux / Mac OS

It has:

a.Its own stack memory (~1MB default)
b.Its own scheduling by OS
c.Heavy system-level resources
d.Problem with OS Threads

Imagine:

-10,000 users hitting your web server
-Each request handled by 1 thread

That means:

10,000 OS threads

Problems:

(i)   Huge memory usage
(ii)  Context switching cost
(iii) System slowdown
(iv)  Hard limit (few thousands max)

This is why people used:

-Thread pools
-Async programming
-Complex reactive frameworks


🔵 Now: Virtual Threads (Java 21+)

Virtual Threads are:

Lightweight threads managed by the JVM, not the OS.

Now the mapping is:

100,000 Virtual Threads
        ↓
Scheduled on maybe 8–16 OS threads


How is this possible?

Let’s break it simply.

🔹 Important Idea: Most threads WAIT most of the time

Example:

String data = databaseCall();

While waiting for database:

-The thread is doing NOTHING.
-Just sitting idle.

Old model:

OS thread is blocked.
Wasting memory and resources.
🔹 What Virtual Threads Do Differently

When a virtual thread blocks (like DB call):

Instead of:

Blocking OS thread

It does:

(i)   Save its stack state into heap
(ii)  Free the OS thread
(iii) Let OS thread do other work
(Like Context switching in OS)

Later when DB responds:

-JVM resumes the virtual thread
-Mounts it again on an OS thread

🧠 Key Concept: Mount / Unmount

Mounted → Virtual thread is attached to OS thread
Unmounted → Saved state, waiting

This is why they scale massively.

🔥 Why They Are Lightweight

Platform thread:

-Stack in OS memory
-Fixed size (~1MB)

Virtual thread:

(i)  Stack stored in heap
(ii) Grows dynamically
(iii) Much smaller

You can create:

Millions of virtual threads

Without crashing system.

🧠 Why This Matters for GC

Virtual thread stacks are:

a.Stored in heap
b.Managed by GC
c.Cleaned automatically

So memory is more efficient.